        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The SFR in PKS~2005-489  determined from measurements of  the H$\alpha$ luminosity of the circumnuclear star forming  ring  is  SFR(H$\alpha$) = $1.2~M_{\odot}~yr^{-1}$ [1].  Hence an  estimate for  the  far-infrared luminosity (L$_{FIR}$) of the star forming material from the  circumnuclear ring can  be approximated  by assuming  SFR(H$\alpha$) $\sim$ SFR(L$_{FIR}$). Then by using the empirical expressions presented in [12],  we find that the far-infrared emission arising from the ongoing star formation ring is about L$_{FIR} =7 \times 10^{9} $ L$_{\odot}$.  From the results presented in Table 2 of  [13], we  assume a luminosity ratio  L$_{FIR}$/L'$_{CO} \sim 30$,  where L'$_{CO}$  is the CO line luminosity, yielding a CO line luminosity     of  L'$_{CO} = 0.23 \times 10^{9} $ K km s$^{-1}$ pc$^{-2}$. \smallskip

Following the definition for CO line luminosity given  in [14],  we calculate  a velocity integrated flux  of S$_{CO(1-0)} \Delta v = 1 $  Jy km s$^{-1}$. According to [1], the observed average radial velocity of the star forming ring is $V_{r} \sim 75$ km s$^{-1}$, hence we expect that  the integrated flux density in the CO J = 1-0 integrated flux is    S$_{CO (1-0)} = 13.33$ mJy.  We further assume a 5$\sigma$ value to a proper detection of the line and then  the sensitivity  required to detect  integrated emission from the whole ring should be about 2.66 mJy. We propose to use C32-1 (most compact)  configuration of the array  to resolve the star forming ring,  which assures moderate spatial resolution ($\sim 3.5$ arcsec)  but also an optimum sensitivity to all spatial frequencies in the maps. Then, taking into account the dimensions of the star forming ring (inner radius = 1.5~arcsec,  outer radius = 3.5~arcsec), four ALMA beams in the most compact configuration will  sample the whole ring and  the required sensitivity  per pointing  to detect the $^{12}$CO(1-0) emission line at  5$\sigma $  should be about  2.66 mJy~/~4  = 0.66~mJy. \smallskip


The spectral set up for the proposed observations has been  designed to detect $^{12}$CO(1-0) emission. Hence, the representative spectral window is centered at 107.62 GHz with a bandwidth of 1.875 GHz and correlator channel spacing of 976.5 kHz, corresponding to 2.72 km s$^{-1}$,   allowing  to cover the entire $^{12}$CO(1-0) line profile.  The other spectral window  is centered at   95.23 GHz to sample adjacent continuum emission.  According to the ALMA observing tool,  the required time to observe the $^{12}$CO(1-0) emission line in band 3,  using the most compact ALMA  configuration  in order to reach a sensitivity per pointing of 0.65 mJy with a resolution of 15 km s$^{-1}$ (enough to resolve the expected  double-peaked profile )   is  about one hour (\textbf{1.1 hr}).  



</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
