    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The discovery of a star forming ring in the circumnuclear region of the gamma-ray BL Lac object PKS 2005-489 (Bressan et al. 2006, ApJL, 645, 101) provides a unique opportunity to study star formation in an environment where the central AGN and its relativistic jets are very likely to play a pivotal role in producing abnormal physical and chemical conditions for the star forming gas. Here we propose to observe the host galaxy of PKS 2005-489 with ALMA at band 3 to map the 12CO(1-0) emission line arising from a rotating star forming ring located at about 4 kpc (2 arcsec) from the nucleus. With the proposed observations we shall determine for the first time the distribution of the molecular gas reservoir around an AGN with prominent relativistic jets -- powerful enough to accelerate particles up to the highest energies -- and constrain the kinematic properties of the circumnuclear star forming ring.	Ultimately, the proposed observations will allow us to set upper limits to the physical conditions of star forming gas in an extreme environment.</prp:abstract>
